.TH CUSTODIA-CLIENT 1 "@DATE@" "Custodia @VERSION@" "Custodia Manual"
.SH NAME
custodia-client \- encrypted Custodia client CLI
.SH SYNOPSIS
.SY custodia-client
.I command
.RI [ arguments ...]
.YS
.SY custodia-client
.B version
.YS
.SY custodia-client
.B --version
.YS
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B custodia-client
is the end-user encrypted secret CLI for Custodia. It performs application
cryptography locally and sends only ciphertext, crypto metadata, opaque
recipient envelopes, and optional application public-key metadata to the server.
.PP
Passing
.BI --client-id " ID"
uses the standard per-user profile directory:
.PP
.EX
$XDG_CONFIG_HOME/custodia/ID
.EE
.PP
or, when
.B XDG_CONFIG_HOME
is not set:
.PP
.EX
$HOME/.config/custodia/ID
.EE
.PP
Explicit paths and
.BI --config " FILE"
remain available for advanced automation.
.PP
The server may store authenticated application public keys and fingerprints as
metadata for recipient discovery. It is not a trust oracle, and private
application keys never leave the client host.
.SH COMMANDS
.TP
.B mtls enroll --client-id ID --server-url URL --enrollment-token TOKEN [--insecure]
Generate a client-side mTLS private key and CSR, claim a short-lived enrollment token, and install the returned client certificate and CA certificate into the standard profile. TLS certificate validation is enabled by default; use --insecure only for disposable first-run labs with an untrusted local CA. For real remote clients, install the Custodia CA into the client OS trust store before enrollment; see CLIENT_TRUSTED_CA.md. The mTLS private key never leaves the client host. Enrollment failures include an operator hint for token, TLS trust, SAN/hostname, DNS/network, wrong-listener and local-profile overwrite cases.
.TP
.B mtls generate-csr --client-id ID [--private-key-out FILE --csr-out FILE]
Generate a client-side mTLS private key and CSR for manual/offline enrollment workflows.
.TP
.B mtls install-cert --client-id ID --cert-file FILE --ca-file FILE [--cert-out FILE --ca-out FILE]
Install a signed mTLS client certificate and public CA certificate into the standard client profile directory.
.TP
.B config write --client-id ID [--server-url URL --out FILE --cert FILE --key FILE --ca FILE --crypto-key FILE]
Write a reusable local JSON profile for mTLS and local crypto paths. With only
.B --client-id ,
paths and the server URL are derived from the standard client profile directory created by
.BR "mtls enroll" .
.TP
.B config check --client-id ID|--config FILE
Validate the profile, HTTPS URL, local mTLS certificate/key pair, CA bundle,
and optional crypto key without contacting the server.
.TP
.B profile list
List standard per-user client profile ids found under
.I $XDG_CONFIG_HOME/custodia
or
.I $HOME/.config/custodia
when
.B XDG_CONFIG_HOME
is not set. The command ignores non-profile files and never reads
.IR /etc/custodia-client .
.TP
.B profile show --client-id ID
Print local profile metadata and file-presence booleans without exposing private
key content, enrollment tokens, secret values, or private-key file paths.
.TP
.B profile path --client-id ID
Print the resolved standard local profile directory for
.IR ID .
.TP
.B profile export --client-id ID --out FILE [--include-private-keys --yes]
Export the standard local profile to a JSON archive. By default the archive
contains metadata, public certificates, the CSR, server URL, config metadata and
public application key only. Private mTLS and application keys are included only
when
.B --include-private-keys
and
.B --yes
are both supplied. Treat such an archive as secret material.
.TP
.B profile import --file FILE [--client-id ID] [--force]
Import a profile export into the standard XDG/HOME profile location. If
.B --client-id
is supplied, it must match the exported client id. Import refuses to overwrite an
existing profile unless
.B --force
is supplied. The reusable config is normalized to the target host profile path.
Run
.BR "config check --client-id ID"
and then
.BR "doctor --client-id ID --online"
after import.
.TP
.B profile delete --client-id ID --yes
Delete the local per-user profile directory. The explicit
.B --yes
confirmation is required. This removes local files only; it does not revoke the
client on the server, delete secrets, revoke access grants, or rotate keys.
.TP
.B key generate --client-id ID [--private-key-out FILE --public-key-out FILE]
Generate a local X25519 application key pair. Without explicit output paths,
write
.I ID.x25519.json
and
.I ID.x25519.pub.json
under the standard client profile directory.
.TP
.B key public --client-id ID --private-key FILE --public-key-out FILE
Derive and write a local public key file from a private key file.
.TP
.B key inspect --key FILE
Print key metadata and public-key fingerprint without exposing private material.
.TP
.B key publish --client-id ID|--config FILE [--crypto-key FILE]
Publish the authenticated client's application public key and SHA-256 fingerprint
to Custodia metadata. The X25519 private key remains local.
.TP
.B doctor --client-id ID|--config FILE [--online]
Run read-only diagnostics for a local client profile. The default mode validates
local profile, mTLS files, CA bundle and crypto key without contacting the server.
Pass
.B --online
for an mTLS current-client reachability check. Use
.BR "profile show"
for a non-validating inventory of the local profile files.
.TP
.B secret put --client-id ID|--config FILE --key KEY [--namespace NS] --value-file FILE [--recipient ID|ID=FILE] [--permissions read[,write,share]|all|BITS]
Encrypt a plaintext file locally and create a secret in the caller-visible namespace/key keyspace.
.TP
.B secret get --client-id ID|--config FILE --key KEY [--namespace NS] [--out FILE]
Read a secret by namespace/key, decrypt locally, and write plaintext output with mode 0600.
.TP
.B secret share --client-id ID|--config FILE --key KEY [--namespace NS] --target-client-id ID [--recipient ID=FILE] [--permissions read[,write,share]|all|BITS]
Grant another client access by rewrapping local key material to the target
recipient public key. Without a pinned
.B --recipient
override, the CLI resolves the target from server-published public-key metadata.
Sharing fails when the target already has the same namespace/key in its visible
keyspace.
.TP
.B secret update --client-id ID|--config FILE --key KEY [--namespace NS] --value-file FILE [--recipient ID|ID=FILE] [--permissions read[,write,share]|all|BITS]
Create a new encrypted version. Include every recipient that should keep access.
.TP
.B secret versions --client-id ID|--config FILE --key KEY [--namespace NS] [--limit N]
List secret version metadata.
.TP
.B secret access list --client-id ID|--config FILE --key KEY [--namespace NS] [--limit N]
List access grant metadata.
.TP
.B secret access revoke --client-id ID|--config FILE --key KEY [--namespace NS] --target-client-id ID --yes
Revoke future server-side access for a target client. Only the owner can revoke
other clients. Already downloaded material may remain decryptable offline.
.TP
.B secret delete --client-id ID|--config FILE --key KEY [--namespace NS] [--cascade] --yes
Delete a caller-visible key. Non-owners remove only their own visibility; owners
are blocked while the key is still shared unless --cascade is supplied.
.SH GLOBAL OPTIONS
.TP
.BI --client-id " ID"
Local client id. For most commands this selects the standard per-user profile.
Also accepted through
.BR CUSTODIA_CLIENT_ID .
.TP
.BI --config " FILE"
Reusable client profile. Also accepted through
.BR CUSTODIA_CLIENT_CONFIG .
.TP
.BI --server-url " URL"
Custodia API base URL.
.TP
.BI --cert " FILE"
Client mTLS certificate.
.TP
.BI --key " FILE"
Client mTLS private key for non-secret commands. In secret commands,
.B --key
identifies the secret; use
.BI --mtls-key " FILE"
for an explicit mTLS private key path.
.TP
.BI --mtls-key " FILE"
Client mTLS private key for secret commands, where
.B --key
is reserved for the secret key.
.TP
.BI --ca " FILE"
Custodia CA certificate. For normal client profiles, use a readable client-local copy such as
.I ca.crt
instead of loosening /etc/custodia permissions.
.TP
.BI --crypto-key " FILE"
Local X25519 private key JSON.
.TP
.BI --recipient " ID=FILE"
Recipient client id resolved from server-published metadata, or pinned public key
override as
.BR ID=FILE .
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B XDG_CONFIG_HOME
Base directory for standard Custodia client profiles. Defaults to
.IR $HOME/.config .
.TP
.B CUSTODIA_CLIENT_ID
Default local client id.
.TP
.B CUSTODIA_CLIENT_CONFIG
Default reusable profile path.
.TP
.B CUSTODIA_BASE_URL
Default API base URL.
.TP
.B CUSTODIA_CLIENT_CERT
Default mTLS client certificate.
.TP
.B CUSTODIA_CLIENT_KEY
Default mTLS client private key.
.TP
.B CUSTODIA_CA_CERT
Default CA certificate.
.TP
.B CUSTODIA_CRYPTO_KEY
Default local X25519 private key file.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I $HOME/.config/custodia/ID/ID.config.json
Reusable local client profile written by
.BR "custodia-client config write" .
.TP
.I $HOME/.config/custodia/ID/ID.key
Client-side mTLS private key generated by
.BR "custodia-client mtls generate-csr" .
.TP
.I $HOME/.config/custodia/ID/ID.x25519.json
Local application private key. Keep mode 0600.
.TP
.I $HOME/.config/custodia/ID/ID.x25519.pub.json
Local application public key. It can be published with
.BR "custodia-client key publish"
or exchanged out of band for pinned workflows.
.SH SECURITY NOTES
Plaintext, DEKs, mTLS private keys and application private keys remain outside
the server. Server-published application public keys are discovery metadata, not
a substitute for caller-side trust or pinning policy. Avoid writing plaintext to
stdout on shared terminals.
.PP
Profile exports created with
.B --include-private-keys
contain operational client identity material. Protect the JSON archive like any
other private-key backup, transfer it only over a trusted channel, and remove
temporary copies after import.
.PP
Revoking access is future server-side revocation. For strong revocation, create
a new encrypted version without the removed recipient.
.SH EXAMPLES
Create and validate a local client profile:
.PP
.EX
CLIENT_ID=client_alice
CUSTODIA_SERVER_URL=https://vault.example:8443
CUSTODIA_ENROLLMENT_TOKEN=PASTE_TOKEN_HERE
custodia-client mtls enroll --client-id "$CLIENT_ID" \
  --server-url "$CUSTODIA_SERVER_URL" \
  --enrollment-token "$CUSTODIA_ENROLLMENT_TOKEN"
custodia-client key generate --client-id "$CLIENT_ID"
custodia-client config write --client-id "$CLIENT_ID"
custodia-client key publish --client-id "$CLIENT_ID"
custodia-client config check --client-id "$CLIENT_ID"
.EE
.PP
Create and read a secret:
.PP
.EX
custodia-client secret put --client-id client_alice \
  --key demo --value-file secret.txt
custodia-client secret get --client-id client_alice \
  --key demo --out secret.readback.txt
.EE
.SH VERSION
Custodia version: @VERSION@
.br
Build commit: @COMMIT@
.br
Build date: @DATE@
.PP
Runtime version is available with:
.PP
.EX
custodia-client version
.EE
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success.
.TP
.B 1
Runtime or API failure.
.TP
.B 2
Usage error.
.SH SEE ALSO
.IR docs/DOCTOR.md ,
.BR custodia-admin (1),
.BR custodia-server (1),
.BR custodia-signer (1)
